{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519951","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519951"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:05+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:18:05+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13113"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13113","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13113"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.46,0.08,0.08,0.35,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5550"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111068"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5550","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5550"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13113"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93189"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"5"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"24"},{"type":"tags","id":"36"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"93"},{"type":"tags","id":"1051"},{"type":"tags","id":"1052"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"},{"type":"tags","id":"1291"},{"type":"tags","id":"2924"},{"type":"tags","id":"12919"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9390"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9608"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40963"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45135"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111068","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/111068"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 43-year-old woman presents to the Emergency Department with a four-hour history of left flank pain radiating to her left groin. The pain was sudden in onset, initially mild but has been worsening over the past two hours and is now constant and excruciating. She has had nausea and vomiting, but no fevers, chills or blood in her urine. She has a medical history of Crohn\u0027s disease. Her regular medication is mesalazine. She works as a teacher and has no recent travel history. On examination, she appears unwell and is writhing in pain. Her pulse rate is 93/min, blood pressure 148/88 mmHg, respiratory rate 24/min, SpO2 98% on room air, and temperature 36.7\u00b0C. She has marked tenderness along the left flank. Investigations reveal:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrinalysis: 2+ haematuria\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHaemoglobin: 119 g/L (120-160)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EWhite cell count: 8.2 x10\u003Csup\u003E9\u003C/sup\u003E/L (4.5-11.0)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECreatinine: 79.6 \u00b5mol/L (45-84)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EUrea: 4.9 mmol/L (2.5-7.8)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate dietary advice for prevention of future stones?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Restrict dietary calcium intake","Reduce fruit and vegetable intake","Increase consumption of spinach and nuts","Reduce dietary sodium intake","Increase protein intake"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient most likely has a calcium oxalate stone, which is particularly common in patients with Crohn\u0027s disease due to increased oxalate absorption in the gastrointestinal tract. This occurs as higher quantities of bile salts and fatty acids are present in the gut due to malabsorption, which bind to intestinal calcium resulting in less calcium being available to bind and trap intestinal oxalate. This causes an increase in free oxalate that can be absorbed, eventually making it back to the kidneys to be excreted.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe key to preventing recurrence is understanding the role of diet in stone formation. \u003Cstrong\u003EReduce dietary sodium intake\u003C/strong\u003E is recommended as it helps decrease urinary calcium excretion. High sodium intake increases urinary calcium excretion and thus the risk of calcium stone formation. This, combined with adequate fluid intake, is one of the most effective dietary modifications for preventing calcium oxalate stones.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERestrict dietary calcium intake\u003C/strong\u003E is actually counterproductive and potentially harmful. Adequate dietary calcium is important as it binds to oxalate in the gut, reducing oxalate absorption and subsequent urinary oxalate excretion. Low calcium diets can increase the risk of stone formation.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduce fruit and vegetable intake\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as most fruits and vegetables are beneficial for stone prevention. They provide citrate, which inhibits stone formation, and their alkalinising effect on urine helps prevent calcium oxalate crystallisation. Only specific high-oxalate vegetables need to be limited.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease consumption of spinach and nuts\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as these foods are high in oxalate. Patients with calcium oxalate stones should limit intake of high-oxalate foods including spinach, rhubarb, nuts, and chocolate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncrease protein intake\u003C/strong\u003E would be inappropriate as high protein intake can increase urinary calcium excretion and decrease urinary citrate, both of which increase the risk of stone formation.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Dietary calcium should not be restricted in calcium oxalate stones as it binds oxalate in the gut and reduces absorption.","Reducing dietary sodium helps prevent calcium oxalate stone formation by decreasing urinary calcium excretion.","High oxalate foods should be limited in patients with calcium oxalate stones."],"references":["Nojaba L, Guzman N. Nephrolithiasis. [Updated 2022 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2023 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK559227/","Kidney stone diet plan and prevention. In: National Kidney Foundation [online]. Accessed 2025 Jul 22. Available at: https://www.kidney.org/kidney-topics/kidney-stone-diet-plan-and-prevention","Han H, Segal AM, Seifter JL, Dwyer JT. Nutritional Management of Kidney Stones (Nephrolithiasis). Clin Nutr Res. 2015 Jul;4(3):137-52. Available at: https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC4525130/","Betz M. Whole Diet Approach to Calcium Oxalate Kidney Stone Prevention. J Ren Nutr. 2022 Jan;32(1):e11-e17. Available from: https://www.jrnjournal.org/article/S1051-2276%2821%2900268-5/fulltext"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93189"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13113"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"93189","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/93189"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-08-07T22:29:58+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-08-07T22:32:33+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5550"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"111068"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"5","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/5"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2d","name":"Gastroenterology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:43+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags